The paper deals with a problem in distributed control involving a networked system of autonomous agents cooperating to carry out some complex task in a decentralized fashion. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also presents a randomized algorithm for computing the average in networks with directed, time-varying communication topologies, which suggests that it could also belong to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) and Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. The paper further discusses the constraints of finite memory and channel capacity, which suggests that it could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of consensus, which suggests that it could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
